&gt;     15.00 per hour (I think that's way too high and would hurt businesses)
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; $15 would just be keeping up with inflation as the real wage has decreased dramatically over the years. This would also be a living wage, so people could actually survive while working 40 hours a week. Some businesses wouldn't be able to keep up but I think most will be able to handle it. If a business can't give its employees a living wage, it's not a very good business.
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt;     making college tuition free
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; This would probably allow us to see a decrease in the outrageous college tuition rates you mentioned. With the proper funding this can work. Plus there are major positive social and economic externalities that come with a more educated society. It also allows people to gain an education regardless of their class background, so it is a moral victory as well.
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt;     I feel like Joe Biden, right now, is the most electable and I would support him if he here to jump into the race
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; That seems ridiculous. You don't know any of his positions, ideas, policies. He hasn't released any of this. You're purely speculating here. Placing your bets on a man who you have no information on of how he will run the country is way more unrealistic than supporting Bernie Sanders.

Corporate taxes are too high, that's why so many companies avoid paying taxes here. A lower corporate tax rate would bring in more money, not less. If we eliminated loop holes and lowered the tax rate, the country would benefit. 

It doesn't matter that $15.00/hour would be "keeping up with inflation," it would dramatically increase inflation and run a lot of businesses out of business and we would lose jobs. 

As far as tuition prices, there would have to be a major reduction in cost before we could do it, we couldn't just start by footing the bill as it is and hope for reduction, it just doesn't work that way and that's very idealistic. 

Now, with Biden, we do know a lot about his political goals. He's been a candidate before, he's been involved with a lot of debates, and if I have agreed with him in the past, and I like the current administration, it's not that out there to assume I would like him as a candidate.
